<p><b>Bayes' theorem</b> (alternatively <b>Bayes' law</b> or <b>Bayes' rule=
</b>, after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Bayes" title=3D=
"Thomas Bayes">Thomas Bayes</a> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><s=
pan class=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span s=
tyle=3D"border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"'b' in 'buy'">b</span><spa=
n title=3D"/e=C9=AA/: 'a' in 'face'">e=C9=AA</span><span title=3D"'z' in 'z=
oom'">z</span></span>/</a></span></span>)) gives a mathematical rule for in=
verting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_probability" t=
itle=3D"Conditional probability">conditional probabilities</a>, allowing th=
e probability of a cause to be found given its effect. For example, with Ba=
yes' theorem, the probability that a patient has a disease given that they =
tested positive for that disease can be found using the probability that th=
e test yields a positive result when the disease is present. The theorem wa=
s developed in the 18th century by Bayes and independently by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-Simon Lap=
lace">Pierre-Simon Laplace</a>.
</p><p>One of Bayes' theorem's many applications is <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=3D"Bayesian inference">Bayesian=
 inference</a>, an approach to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sta=
tistical_inference" title=3D"Statistical inference">statistical inference</=
a>, where it is used to invert the probability of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Realization_(probability)" title=3D"Realization (probabilit=
y)">observations</a> given a model configuration (i.e., the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood_function" title=3D"Likelihood function=
">likelihood function</a>) to obtain the probability of the model configura=
tion given the observations (i.e., the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"Posterior probability">posterior proba=
bility</a>).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayes%27_theorem&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Bayes' theorem is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
homas_Bayes" title=3D"Thomas Bayes">Thomas Bayes</a>, a minister, statistic=
ian, and philosopher. Bayes used conditional probability to provide an algo=
rithm (his Proposition 9) that uses evidence to calculate limits on an unkn=
own parameter. His work was published in 1763 as <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/An_Essay_Towards_Solving_a_Problem_in_the_Doctrine_of_Cha=
nces" title=3D"An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chance=
s">An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances</a></i>. B=
ayes studied how to compute a distribution for the probability parameter of=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=3D=
"Binomial distribution">binomial distribution</a> (in modern terminology). =
After Bayes's death, his family gave his papers to a friend, the minister, =
philosopher, and mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ric=
hard_Price" title=3D"Richard Price">Richard Price</a>.
</p><p>Price significantly edited the unpublished manuscript for two years =
before sending it to a friend who read it aloud at the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Society" title=3D"Royal Society">Royal Society</=
a> on 23 December 1763.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Liberty's_Apostle_1-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_n=
ote-Liberty's_Apostle-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Price edited<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#=
cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> Bayes's major work "An Essay Towards Solving a Prob=
lem in the Doctrine of Chances" (1763), which appeared in <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophical_Transactions" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Philosophical Transactions">Philosophical Transactions</a></i>,<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Price1763_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-Price1763-3"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and =
contains Bayes' theorem. Price wrote an introduction to the paper that prov=
ides some of the philosophical basis of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Bayesian_statistics" title=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian statistic=
s</a> and chose one of the two solutions Bayes offered. In 1765, Price was =
elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in recognition of his work on Bayes's=
 legacy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Holland46_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-Holland46-4"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On 27 April, a letter=
 sent to his friend <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Frank=
lin" title=3D"Benjamin Franklin">Benjamin Franklin</a> was read out at the =
Royal Society, and later published, in which Price applies this work to pop=
ulation and computing 'life-annuities'.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EB1911_6-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#c=
ite_note-EB1911-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Independently of Bayes, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pie=
rre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-Simon Laplace">Pierre-Simon Laplace</a> =
used conditional probability to formulate the relation of an updated <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"Posterio=
r probability">posterior probability</a> from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Prior_probability" title=3D"Prior probability">prior probabil=
ity</a>, given evidence. He reproduced and extended Bayes's results in 1774=
, apparently unaware of Bayes's work, and summarized his results in <i><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9orie_analytique_des_probabilit=
%C3%A9s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Th=C3=A9orie analytique des probabi=
lit=C3=A9s">Th=C3=A9orie analytique des probabilit=C3=A9s</a></i> (1812).<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>n=
ote 1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theor=
em#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bay=
esian_probability" title=3D"Bayesian probability">Bayesian interpretation</=
a> of probability was developed mainly by Laplace.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem=
#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>About 200 years later, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haro=
ld_Jeffreys" title=3D"Harold Jeffreys">Sir Harold Jeffreys</a> put Bayes's =
algorithm and Laplace's formulation on an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Axiomatic_system" title=3D"Axiomatic system">axiomatic</a> basis, w=
riting in a 1973 book that Bayes' theorem "is to the theory of probability =
what the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" titl=
e=3D"Pythagorean theorem">Pythagorean theorem</a> is to geometry".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Jeffreys1973_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-Jeffreys1973-10"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Stigler" title=3D"S=
tephen Stigler">Stephen Stigler</a> used a Bayesian argument to conclude th=
at Bayes' theorem was discovered by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Nicholas_Saunderson" title=3D"Nicholas Saunderson">Nicholas Saunderson</a=
>, a blind English mathematician, some time before Bayes,<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27=
_theorem#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stats,_Data_and_Mod=
els_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baye=
s%27_theorem#cite_note-Stats,_Data_and_Models-12"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but that is d=
isputed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Martyn Hooper<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-14"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> an=
d Sharon McGrayne<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mcgrayne2011theory_15-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-=
mcgrayne2011theory-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> have argued that Richard Price's contr=
ibution was substantial:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>By modern standards, we should refer=
 to the Bayes=E2=80=93Price rule. Price discovered Bayes's work, recognized=
 its importance, corrected it, contributed to the article, and found a use =
for it. The modern convention of employing Bayes's name alone is unfair but=
 so entrenched that anything else makes little sense.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mc=
grayne2011theory_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-mcgrayne2011theory-15"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p><=
/blockquote>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F._Thomas_Bruss" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"F. Thomas Bruss">F. Thomas Bruss</a> reviewed Bayes's "An =
essay towards solving a problem in the doctrine of chances" as communicated=
 by Price.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He agrees wi=
th Stigler's analysis in many points, but not as far as the question of pri=
ority is concerned. Bruss underlines the intuitive part of Bayes's formula =
and adds independent arguments of Bayes's probable motivation for his work.=
 He concludes that, unless the contrary is really proven, we are entitled t=
o be faithful to the name "Bayes' Theorem" or "Bayes' formula".
</p>
