<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Drug_testing">Drug testing<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayes%27_the=
orem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Drug testing=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Suppose, a particular test for whether someone has been using cannabis i=
s 90% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensitivity_(tests)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sensitivity (tests)">sensitive</a>, meaning the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/True_positive_rate" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"True positive rate">true positive rate</a> (TPR) =3D 0.90. =
Therefore, it leads to 90% true positive results (correct identification of=
 drug use) for cannabis users.
</p><p>The test is also 80% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Specif=
icity_(tests)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Specificity (tests)">specific=
</a>, meaning <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/True_negative_rate" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"True negative rate">true negative rate</a> (=
TNR) =3D 0.80. Therefore, the test correctly identifies 80% of non-use for =
non-users, but also generates 20% false positives, or <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/False_positive_rate" title=3D"False positive rate">fals=
e positive rate</a> (FPR) =3D 0.20, for non-users.
</p><p>Assuming 0.05 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prevalence" t=
itle=3D"Prevalence">prevalence</a>, meaning 5% of people use cannabis, what=
 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Prob=
ability">probability</a> that a random person who tests positive is really =
a cannabis user?
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_predictive_val=
ue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive predictive value">Positive pred=
ictive value</a> (PPV) of a test is the proportion of persons who are actua=
lly positive out of all those testing positive, and can be calculated from =
a sample as:
</p>
<dl><dd>PPV =3D True positive / Tested positive</dd></dl>
<p>If sensitivity, specificity, and prevalence are known, PPV can be calcul=
ated using Bayes' theorem. Let <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
yle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" a=
lttext=3D"{\displaystyle P({\text{User}}\vert {\text{Positive}})}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>P</mi>
