-align: -2.671ex; width:49.797ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle P(=
X_{C}|Y)=3D{\frac {P(Y|X_{C})P(X_{C})}{P(Y)}}=3D{\frac {0.01\cdot 0.50}{0.0=
24}}=3D{\frac {5}{24}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Given that the item is defective, the probability that it was made by ma=
chine C is 5/24. C produces half of the total output but a much smaller fra=
ction of the defective items. Hence the knowledge that the item selected wa=
s defective enables us to replace the prior probability <i>P</i>(<i>X</i><s=
ub>C</sub>)&nbsp;=3D 1/2 by the smaller posterior probability <i>P</i>(X<su=
b>C</sub>=E2=80=89|=E2=80=89<i>Y</i>)&nbsp;=3D 5/24.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interpretations">Interpreta=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayes%=
27_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Inter=
pretations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bayes_theorem_assassin.svg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/7/7a/Bayes_theorem_assassin.svg/250px-Bayes_theorem_assassin.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"375" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"768"></a><figcaption>A geometric v=
isualization of Bayes' theorem using astronauts who may be suspicious (with=
 eyebrows) and may be assassins (with daggers)</figcaption></figure>
<p>The interpretation of Bayes' rule depends on the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_interpretations" title=3D"Probability interpr=
etations">interpretation of probability</a> ascribed to the terms. The two =
predominant classes of interpretation are described below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bayesian_interpretations">B=
ayesian interpretations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DBayes%27_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"E=
dit section: Bayesian interpretations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_probability" title=
=3D"Bayesian probability">Bayesian (or epistemological) interpretations</a>=
, probability measures a "degree of belief".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#ci=
te_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-23"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Bayes' theorem links the degree of belief in a proposition before and aft=
er accounting for evidence. For example, suppose it is believed with 50% ce=
rtainty that a coin is twice as likely to land heads than tails. If the coi=
n is flipped a number of times and the outcomes observed, that degree of be=
lief will probably rise or fall, but might remain the same, depending on th=
e results. For proposition <i>A</i> and evidence <i>B</i>,
</p>
<ul><li><i>P</i>=E2=80=89(<i>A</i>), the <i>prior</i>, is the initial degre=
e of belief in <i>A</i>.</li>
<li><i>P</i>=E2=80=89(<i>A</i>=E2=80=89|=E2=80=89<i>B</i>), the <i>posterio=
r</i>, is the degree of belief after incorporating news that <i>B</i> is tr=
ue.</li>
<li>the quotient <span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span =
class=3D"num"><i>P</i>(<i>B</i>=E2=80=89|=E2=80=89<i>A</i>)</span><span cla=
ss=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den"><i>P</i>(<i>B</i>)</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span> represents the support <i>B</i> provides for <i>A</i>.</li=
></ul>
<p>For more on the application of Bayes' theorem under Bayesian interpretat=
ions of probability, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_=
inference" title=3D"Bayesian inference">Bayesian inference</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Frequentist_interpretations=
">Frequentist interpretations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DBayes%27_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Frequentist interpretations"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bayes_theorem_tree_diagrams.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/6/61/Bayes_theorem_tree_diagrams.svg/250px-Bayes_theorem_tree_diagr=
ams.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"413" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"470" data-file-height=3D"776"></a><figcaptio=
n>Illustration of frequentist interpretation with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Tree_diagram_(probability_theory)" title=3D"Tree diagram (p=
robability theory)">tree diagrams</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequentist_interpretati=
on_of_probability" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Frequentist interpretatio=
n of probability">frequentist interpretations</a>, probability measures a "=
proportion of outcomes".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-24"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> For example, suppose an experiment is performed many times. <i>P</i>(<i>A=
</i>) is the proportion of outcomes with property <i>A</i> (the prior) and =
<i>P</i>(<i>B</i>) is the proportion with property <i>B</i>. <i>P</i>(<i>B<=
/i>=E2=80=89|=E2=80=89<i>A</i>) is the proportion of outcomes with property=
 <i>B</i> <i>out of</i> outcomes with property <i>A</i>, and <i>P</i>(<i>A<=
/i>=E2=80=89|=E2=80=89<i>B</i>) is the proportion of those with <i>A</i> <i=
>out of</i> those with <i>B</i> (the posterior).
</p><p>The role of Bayes' theorem can be shown with tree diagrams. The two =
diagrams partition the same outcomes by <i>A</i> and <i>B</i> in opposite o=
rders, to obtain the inverse probabilities. Bayes' theorem links the differ=
ent partitionings.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Example">Example</h4><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayes%27_theorem&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Example"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bayes_theorem_simple_example_tree.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
