A|B)=3D{\frac {P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>In many applications, for instance in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=3D"Bayesian inference">Bayesian inference<=
/a>, the event <i>B</i> is fixed in the discussion and we wish to consider =
the effect of its having been observed on our belief in various possible ev=
ents <i>A</i>. In such situations the denominator of the last expression, t=
he probability of the given evidence <i>B</i>, is fixed; what we want to va=
ry is <i>A</i>. Bayes' theorem shows that the posterior probabilities are <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proportionality_(mathematics)" titl=
e=3D"Proportionality (mathematics)">proportional</a> to the numerator, so t=
he last equation becomes:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e P(A|B)\propto P(A)\cdot P(B|A).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>P</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=E2=88=9D<!-- =E2=88=9D --></mo>
        <mi>P</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mi>P</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
