<p>Often, for some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_a_=
set" title=3D"Partition of a set">partition</a> {<i>A<sub>j</sub></i>} of t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_space" title=3D"Sample s=
pace">sample space</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample=
_space" title=3D"Sample space">event space</a> is given in terms of <i>P</i=
>(<i>A<sub>j</sub></i>) and <i>P</i>(<i>B</i>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<i>A<sub>j</sub><=
/i>). It is then useful to compute <i>P</i>(<i>B</i>) using the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_total_probability" title=3D"Law of tot=
al probability">law of total probability</a>:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 P(B)=3D\sum _{j}P(B\cap A_{j}),}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
