<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayes%27_the=
orem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Application=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Recreational_mathematics">R=
ecreational mathematics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DBayes%27_theorem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"E=
dit section: Recreational mathematics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Bayes' rule and computing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Condi=
tional_probability" title=3D"Conditional probability">conditional probabili=
ties</a> provide a method to solve a number of popular puzzles, such as the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_Prisoners_problem" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Three Prisoners problem">Three Prisoners problem</a>=
, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monty_Hall_problem" title=3D=
"Monty Hall problem">Monty Hall problem</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Boy_or_Girl_paradox" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boy or G=
irl paradox">Two Child problem</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Two_envelopes_problem" title=3D"Two envelopes problem">Two Envelo=
pes problem</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (April 2025)">citation neede=
d</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Genetics">Genetics</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayes%27_theorem&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Genetics"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In genetics, Bayes' rule can be used to estimate the probability that so=
meone has a specific genotype. Many people seek to assess their chances of =
being affected by a genetic disease or their likelihood of being a carrier =
for a recessive gene of interest. A Bayesian analysis can be done based on =
family history or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_testing"=
 title=3D"Genetic testing">genetic testing</a> to predict whether someone w=
ill develop a disease or pass one on to their children. Genetic testing and=
 prediction is common among couples who plan to have children but are conce=
rned that they may both be carriers for a disease, especially in communitie=
s with low genetic variance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-29"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable">
<tbody><tr>
<th>Hypothesis
</th>
<th>Hypothesis 1: Patient is a carrier
</th>
<th>Hypothesis 2: Patient is not a carrier
</th></tr>
<tr>
<th>Prior Probability
</th>
<td>1/2
</td>
<td>1/2
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>Conditional Probability that all four offspring will be unaffected
</th>
<td>(1/2) =E2=8B=85 (1/2) =E2=8B=85 (1/2) =E2=8B=85 (1/2) =3D 1/16
</td>
<td>About 1
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>Joint Probability
</th>
<td>(1/2) =E2=8B=85 (1/16) =3D 1/32
</td>
<td>(1/2) =E2=8B=85 1 =3D 1/2
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>Posterior Probability
</th>
<td>(1/32) / (1/32 + 1/2) =3D 1/17
</td>
<td>(1/2) / (1/32 + 1/2) =3D 16/17
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Above is an example of a Bayesian analysis table for a female's risk for=
 a disease based on the knowledge that the disease is present in her siblin=
gs but not in her parents or any of her four children. Based solely on the =
status of the subject's siblings and parents, she is equally likely to be a=
 carrier as to be a non-carrier (this likelihood is denoted by the prior hy=
pothesis). The probability that the subject's four sons would all be unaffe=
cted is 1/16 (<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<sp=
an class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=8B=85<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inlin=
e-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><=
span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=
=8B=85<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateSt=
yles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=
=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=8B=85<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated=
-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"f=
rac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></spa=
n>) if she is a carrier and about 1 if she is a non-carrier (this is the co=
nditional probability). The joint probability reconciles these two predicti=
ons by multiplying them together. The last line (the posterior probability)=
 is calculated by dividing the joint probability for each hypothesis by the=
 sum of both joint probabilities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ogino_et_al_2004_30-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theo=
rem#cite_note-Ogino_et_al_2004-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Parental genetic testing can detect around 90% of known disease alle=
les in parents that can lead to carrier or affected status in their childre=
n. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cystic_fibrosis" title=3D"Cysti=
c fibrosis">Cystic fibrosis</a> is a heritable disease caused by an <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominance_(genetics)" title=3D"Dominance =
(genetics)">autosomal recessive</a> mutation on the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cystic_fibrosis_transmembrane_conductance_regulator" titl=
e=3D"Cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator">CFTR</a> gene,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> located on <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromosome_7" title=3D"Chromosome 7">chromosome =
7</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Here is a Bayesian analysis of a female patient with a family histor=
y of cystic fibrosis (CF) who has tested negative for CF, demonstrating how=
 the method was used to determine her risk of having a child born with CF: =
because the patient is unaffected, she is either <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Zygosity" title=3D"Zygosity">homozygous</a> for the wild-typ=
e allele, or heterozygous. To establish prior probabilities, a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punnett_square" title=3D"Punnett square">Punne=
tt square</a> is used, based on the knowledge that neither parent was affec=
ted by the disease but both could have been carriers:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"text-align:center;">
<tbody><tr>
<th style=3D"background:var(--background-color-neutral,#eaecf0);color:inher=
it;background:linear-gradient(to top right,var(--background-color-neutral,#=
eaecf0) 49%,var(--border-color-base,#a2a9b1) 49.5%,var(--border-color-base,=
#a2a9b1) 50.5%,var(--background-color-neutral,#eaecf0) 51%);line-height:1.2=
;padding:0.1em 0.4em;"><div style=3D"margin-left:2em;text-align:right">Moth=
er</div><div style=3D"margin-right:2em;text-align:left"><br><br>Father</div=
>
</th>
<th>W
<p>Homozygous for the wild-<br>type allele (a non-carrier)
</p>
</th>
<th>M
<p>Heterozygous<br>(a CF carrier)
</p>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<th>W
<p>Homozygous for the wild-<br>type allele (a non-carrier)
</p>
</th>
<td>WW
</td>
<td>MW
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>M
<p>Heterozygous (a CF carrier)
</p>
</th>
<td>MW
</td>
<td>MM
<p>(affected by cystic fibrosis)
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Given that the patient is unaffected, there are only three possibilities=
. Within these three, there are two scenarios in which the patient carries =
the mutant allele. Thus the prior probabilities are <link rel=3D"mw-dedupli=
cated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=
=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">2</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">3</span>=
</span> and <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Temp=
lateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=
=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">3</span></span>.
</p><p>Next, the patient undergoes genetic testing and tests negative for c=
ystic fibrosis. This test has a 90% detection rate, so the conditional prob=
abilities of a negative test are 1/10 and 1. Finally, the joint and posteri=
or probabilities are calculated as before.
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"text-align:center;">
<tbody><tr>
<th>Hypothesis
</th>
<th>Hypothesis 1: Patient is a carrier
</th>
<th>Hypothesis 2: Patient is not a carrier
</th></tr>
<tr>
<th>Prior Probability
</th>
<td>2/3
</td>
<td>1/3
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>Conditional Probability of a negative test
</th>
<td>1/10
</td>
<td>1
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>Joint Probability
</th>
<td>1/15
</td>
<td>1/3
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>Posterior Probability
</th>
<td>1/6
</td>
<td>5/6
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>After carrying out the same analysis on the patient's male partner (with=
 a negative test result), the chance that their child is affected is the pr=
oduct of the parents' respective posterior probabilities for being carriers=
 times the chance that two carriers will produce an affected offspring (<li=
nk rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r115=
4941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span cl=
ass=3D"den">4</span></span>).
</p><p>Bayesian analysis can be done using phenotypic information associate=
d with a genetic condition. When combined with genetic testing, this analys=
is becomes much more complicated. Cystic fibrosis, for example, can be iden=
tified in a fetus with an ultrasound looking for an echogenic bowel, one th=
at appears brighter than normal on a scan. This is not a foolproof test, as=
 an echogenic bowel can be present in a perfectly healthy fetus. Parental g=
enetic testing is very influential in this case, where a phenotypic facet c=
an be overly influential in probability calculation. In the case of a fetus=
 with an echogenic bowel, with a mother who has been tested and is known to=
 be a CF carrier, the posterior probability that the fetus has the disease =
is very high (0.64). But once the father has tested negative for CF, the po=
sterior probability drops significantly (to 0.16).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ogino=
_et_al_2004_30-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Bayes%27_theorem#cite_note-Ogino_et_al_2004-30"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Risk factor calculation is a powerful tool in genetic counseling and=
 reproductive planning but cannot be treated as the only important factor. =
As above, incomplete testing can yield falsely high probability of carrier =
status, and testing can be financially inaccessible or unfeasible when a pa=
rent is not present.
</p>
